qbone on Debian
===============

Run qbone-setup and you are done:

    sudo qbone-setup

It settles the boot configuration, checks that the PRUs and the cape are
there, bridges the uplink so the emulated machine can reach the network,
tells the emulated Ethernet controller which interface to bind to, and
starts the services. It prints the address to point a browser at.

Running it again is harmless. If a bridge already carries the uplink it is
kept as it is, rather than rebuilt.

On a kernel newer than 4.19 the first run usually changes /boot/uEnv.txt and
stops there, because those settings only take effect at boot:

    sudo qbone-setup      # applies boot settings, asks for a reboot
    sudo reboot
    sudo qbone-setup      # finishes

The original file is kept as /boot/uEnv.txt.qbone-orig.

Boot settings
-------------

bone_capemgr was removed in 4.19, so the cape overlay no longer loads from
the cape's own EEPROM and U-Boot applies it instead. qbone-setup names
QBone.dtbo in a free overlay slot, and turns off three overlays that would
otherwise claim the cape's pins first - the eMMC's, HDMI's and the audio
codec's. It also comments out uboot_overlay_pru: that overlay names a
PRU-ICSS compatible no driver has bound since 6.10, so applying it takes the
PRUs away rather than providing them.

Beyond the cape's pins, QBone.dtbo declares the memory the emulated machine
runs in and the interrupt the PRUs raise. uio_pdrv_genirq binds to the
latter only when told which compatible to look for, which
/etc/modprobe.d/qbone.conf does.

If qbone-setup reports a missing piece it names which one, and each maps to
one of these settings.

Bridging the uplink moves this board's address onto the bridge, which is
the one step that could put a headless board out of reach. qbone-setup arms
a rollback before it makes the change and only cancels it once the gateway
answers through the new bridge; a board that goes silent restores its old
configuration by itself within ninety seconds.

Both the change and the rollback run detached, so losing the session that
started them does not interrupt either. The address is preserved across the
change, so an ssh session usually survives it; if it does not, reconnect and
read /run/qbone-setup.status.

A wireless uplink is refused: a station may not forward frames carrying an
address the access point never saw, so the emulated machine cannot be
reached over one.

To skip the network entirely:

    sudo qbone-setup --no-bridge

The emulated machine can then reach this board, which is enough for a local
mopd, but not the rest of the network.

What it sets up
---------------

The controller binds a raw socket to its own interface, because one on the
uplink cannot reach the BeagleBone itself. That interface is a veth pair,
created from /etc/qbone/network.conf before the emulator starts, with its
far end on the bridge.

The bridge stanza is written to /etc/network/interfaces.d/qbone, with the
uplink's own address pinned so the DHCP lease does not change. A worked
example is in /usr/share/doc/qbone/examples/interfaces-bridge for anyone
configuring it by hand.

Running
-------

qbone-setup starts and enables the services. Afterwards they behave as any
others:

    systemctl status qbone
    systemctl restart qbone

The web interface answers on port 80. State - disk images, saved
configurations and settings.json - lives in /var/lib/qbone.

/usr/bin/qbone serves the web interface and has no menu. The machine a board
comes up as is a saved configuration: add "--config <name>" to the unit's
ExecStart to apply one at startup. /usr/bin/qbone-demo is the same emulation
driven from a terminal menu, for bus latch, master/slave and device exerciser
work; it needs an operator on stdin and is not what the service runs.

The emulated Ethernet controller binds to veth-pdp, the interface
qbone-network creates and joins to the bridge qbone-setup builds from the
uplink. Rename it in /etc/qbone/network.conf and the delqa's "interface"
parameter has to follow.

Admin password
--------------

A board that has no password answers every request, which is what makes a
freshly installed one reachable. Open the interface and it asks for a
password before anything else; from then on the browser asks for it on every
visit, and any user name is accepted. It is stored in settings.json as a
PBKDF2-HMAC-SHA256 digest, so that file becomes readable only by root.

Open the interface promptly after installing. Until a password is set, anyone
who can reach port 80 can operate the machine.

Setting WEBUI_PASSWORD in the service's environment overrides all of this:
the password is then whatever the variable says and the interface will not
change it.

The service runs as root: the PRU driver maps physical memory and the bus
engine needs realtime scheduling priority.
